prereq.html.title: Pre-Requisites
prereq.html.body:
Pre-Requisites
This guide will walk you through getting started with building web and mobile cloud native apps on Bluemix.
Before you begin, make sure you have a Bluemix account

Ready to move to next step?

SETUP.html.title: Setting Up
SETUP.html.body:
Setting up your Environment
In this step you will set up your local development environment.
Download the Bluemix Command Line interface for: MacOS, Linux, Windows
Prefer to get started from a Web GUI instead? Go to the Bluemix Developer Console
You can now use the bx command from your command prompt. The Bluemix command line interface allows you to interact with the Bluemix platform from your desktop.
Next, download the Bluemix CLI Developer plugin for: MacOS, Linux, Windows
You can now use the bx dev command from your command prompt. The Bluemix CLI Developer plugin adds additional functionality to the Bluemix CLI to help a Bluemix developer build Cloud Native applications that follow best practices.  
You will also need the following tools on your development environment (external links):
Xcode
Git
Docker Engine

Ready to move to next step?

BEGIN.html.title: Begin from a Starter
BEGIN.html.body:
Begin with a Starter
In this step you will prepare your project and application.
Navigate to a new directory and run the following command in terminal or command shell:
bx dev create  -p Web -l swift
This command prepares a basic Kitura web server application that is ready to be deployed to the cloud. The application is managed in a Project on Bluemix where you can add additonal cloud services such as Cloudant and App-ID. Learn more about Projects.
Starters are production-ready starter applications that follow Cloud Native architecture Patterns and best practices. Learn more about Starters and Patterns.
Next, run the following command in terminal or command shell to get the code:
bx dev code 
This command downloads the production-ready Starter code to your directory.

Ready to move to next step?

RUNDEBUG.html.title: Run and Debug Locally
RUNDEBUG.html.body:
Run and Debug Locally
In this step you will build and run the application locally on your machine.
Unzip the Starter code. Run the following command in terminal or command shell:
bx dev run
This command builds and runs the application on your machine. The application is built and run inside a local container so that your local runtime environment matches the cloud environment.
Open a web browser navigate to the following address to test your app:
'http://localhost:8080

Ready to move to next step?

IDE.html.title: Set up your IDE
IDE.html.body:
Set up your IDE
In this step you will set up your IDE to edit the Starter code.
On MacOS, run the following commands from your Terminal window to configure an Xcode project:
swift package generate-xcodeproj
open ./Application.xcodeproj
You can now edit your code in Xcode. You can build and debug your code in Xcode as well, but note that the Darwin (MacOS) platform has slight variations from the Linux (Bluemix cloud) platform.
On Linux and Windows Atom, VScode or vi can be used to edit your code.
On all platforms, the Bluemix CLI Developer plugin includes the local runtime and compiler necessary to locally build and test your code for the cloud. Follow the "Run and debug locally" step in this guide to perform this function.

Ready to move to next step?

DEPLOY.html.title: Deploy to the Cloud
DEPLOY.html.body:
Deploy to Bluemix
In this step you will deploy your code to the cloud.
Each Starter supports both Cloud Foundry and IBM Containers deployment models. Learn more about Cloud Foundry and IBM Containers.
This step will use a manual deployment approach. Advance to the "Add an automated DevOps toolchain" step of this guide to use an automated build and deployment approach using the IBM DevOps Toolchain.
For a Cloud Foundry deployment, run the following commands in your terminal or command prompt to deploy and build your app in Bluemix:
bx push
The manifest.yml  configuration file included in the Starter project details configuration parameters for your Cloud Foundry app, including memory and path. Learn more about deploying Cloud Foundry apps.

Ready to move to next step?

LOGS.html.title: View Logs
LOGS.html.body:
View your Logs
In this step you will explore using the IBM Monitoring and Logging feature.
Navigate to the Bluemix Monitoring and Logging dashboard:  https://logmet.ng.bluemix.net
Bluemix automatically collects logs via an ELK technology stack (Elastic Search, Logstash and Kibana) and monitors your application via a Graphite and Grafana technology stack. These are aggregated in the Bluemix Monitoring and Logging dashboard. Learn more.

Ready to move to next step?

DATABASE.html.title: Add a Database
DATABASE.html.body:
Adding a Database
In this step you will add a Cloudant NoSQL database to your application.
Run the following command in your terminal or command prompt:
bx dev edit 
bx dev ??

TOOLCHAIN.html.title: Add an Automated DevOps Toolchain
TOOLCHAIN.html.body:
Add a DevOps Toolchain
In this step you will add an automated DevOps pipeline using the Bluemix DevOps Toolchain. Each Starter includes a toolchain.yml file that automatically configures a DevOps toolchain in Bluemix.
Initialize a new github repository for your project using the following commands in your terminal or command prompt:
git init
git remote add origin 
git add .
git commit -m "My Project"
git push
Open a web browser and navigate to your github repository:
'http://github.com//
Next, click on the "Create Toolchain" button to initilize the process. This brings you to Bluemix where you need to perform a manual step to verify your configuration and trigger the creation of the toolchain.
Each Starter project provides a recommended toolchain configuration for an automated build, deploy and delivery process. Learn more about DevOps toolchain.

Ready to move to next step?
